        </div>
        <div class="timeline-story">
          <blockquote>
            WHEN PAGES STARTED THINKING
          </blockquote>
          <P class="muted">
            Static pages eventually felt limiting. This project marked my shift from layout to logic. Using Node.js, Express, and EJS, I built a blog application where content could be created, rendered, and managed dynamically. For the first time, the server made decisions. I began thinking in flows — requests, responses, state, and reuse. This was where I stopped building pages and started building systems.
          </P>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item four reverse reveal">
        <span class="dot"></span>
        <div class="timeline-image">
          <img src="/public/images/Screenshot 2026-01-29 at 10.52.11 AM.png" />
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-story">
          <blockquote>
            THE WEB DOESN’T LIVE IN ISOLATION
          </blockquote>
          <P class="muted">
            After learning how to control my own data, the next step was understanding external data.
            This project focused on consuming real-world APIs using Axios and transforming raw responses into usable interfaces. I learned how modern applications communicate, fail, recover, and adapt. It introduced me to uncertainty — latency, errors, incomplete data — and how to design around it. The web, I realized, is a network, not a silo.
          </P>
        </div>
      </div>
